    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided prospectus excerpts, here is a detailed breakdown of what the filing says regarding AI compute expansion, xAI\'s infrastructure, revenue generation, monetization strategies, and the investment timeline:\n\n### 1. AI Compute Expansion\n*   **Massive Market & CapEx Scaling:** The company is targeting a **$26.5 trillion** potential market opportunity for AI. Capital expenditures will scale as quickly as the company can deploy power and compute to meet the exponential demands of frontier AI models and the transition toward Artificial General Intelligence (AGI).\n*   **Terrestrial to Orbital Transition:** Because terrestrial power generation cannot scale fast enough to meet AI\'s energy demands without environmental and regulatory harm, the company plans to transition to **orbital AI compute**. By leveraging space-based solar power (which represents 99.8% of the solar system\'s energy) and SpaceX\'s low launch costs, they aim to deliver compute at a fundamentally lower cost structure than on Earth.\n*   **Hardware & Power Acquisitions:** To support terrestrial expansion, the company is aggressively securing power and hardware. Recent commitments include an **$805 million** turbine purchase agreement (through 2029), a **$2 billion** "Turbine Acquisition" for mobile gas turbines to power data centers, and a **$6.58 billion** equipment lease for AI infrastructure hardware.\n*   **Terafab Chip Initiative:** To alleviate chip shortages and reduce costs, the company is partnering with Tesla and Intel on "Terafab," a manufacturing facility designed to produce **1 terawatt per year** of compute chips. \n\n### 2. xAI Compute Infrastructure\n*   **Gigawatt-Scale Facilities:** xAI (acquired in February 2026 to form the AI segment) is the first company to deploy a coherent gigawatt-scale AI training cluster. Its **COLOSSUS** and **COLOSSUS II** facilities in Memphis, Tennessee, collectively provide approximately **1.0 gigawatt** of compute power, with an additional 400MW planned for the next phase of COLOSSUS II.\n*   **Unprecedented Speed & Cost Efficiency:** Using "first-principles" thinking and extreme vertical integration, xAI brought the first COLOSSUS cluster online in **122 days** (repurposing an existing factory) and COLOSSUS II in just **91 days**. This vastly outpaces the industry benchmark of roughly two years for a 100-megawatt greenfield data center, while achieving considerably lower per-megawatt construction costs.\n*   **Model Training & Inference:** The infrastructure is purpose-built to train frontier models like **Grok 5** (currently training at COLOSSUS II) and to handle complex, low-latency, high-throughput inference workloads at scale.\n\n### 3. Revenue Generation\n*   **Consolidated & Segment Financials:** In 2025, the company generated **$18.67 billion** in consolidated revenue. The Connectivity segment (Starlink) is highly profitable, generating $7.16 billion in Adjusted EBITDA. The Space segment generated $4.08 billion in revenue but operated at a loss due to $3 billion in Starship R&D funding. In Q1 2026, consolidated revenue was $4.69 billion.\n*   **Massive User Base:** The AI segment (spanning Grok and the X platform) has over **1.3 billion active accounts** (as of March 2026) and approximately **550 million monthly active AI users**.\n*   **Advertising:** Advertising on the X platform remains a core revenue driver. The company plans to grow ad revenue per user by using AI-driven targeting to make ads feel like contextually relevant, native content.\n*   **Blockbuster Compute Contracts:** The company has secured massive third-party compute contracts, notably a Cloud Services Agreement with **Anthropic** paying **$1.25 billion per month**, and an **$8.5 billion** deferred services fee from **Cursor**.\n\n### 4. Monetization\n*   **Dual Compute Monetization Strategy:** The company employs a dual strategy: using its vast compute resources for proprietary AI applications (like Grok) while simultaneously monetizing unused/excess capacity by selling it to select third parties (like Anthropic). This allows them to generate immediate returns on invested capital while retaining the right to reallocate capacity for internal use if needed.\n*   **Strategic Partnerships & M&A:** The $8.5 billion Cursor agreement is payable in cash or Class A common stock. It includes collaboration to improve Grok, joint model development, and an option for the company to acquire Cursor outright.\n*   **Consumer & Enterprise AI:** The company plans to increase revenue from its massive consumer and enterprise user base through subscriptions, AI solutions, and performance advertising.\n*   **Orbital Compute Economics:** Long-term monetization relies on launching compute to space, where unlimited solar power and SpaceX\'s launch capabilities will allow the company to offer high-performance compute at margins and cost structures impossible to achieve on Earth.\n\n### 5. Investment Timeline\n*   **Multi-Year AI Investment Horizon:** The company explicitly states it expects a **"multi-year investment horizon"** of heavy capital allocation before the AI segment\'s deployments translate into sustained positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA. \n*   **Near-Term (2026):** \n    *   Anthropic compute capacity ramps up in May and June 2026.\n    *   The $2 billion Turbine Acquisition is expected to close in May 2026.\n    *   COLOSSUS II was brought online in just 91 days in early 2026.\n*   **Mid-Term (2028–2029):** \n    *   The company expects to begin deploying its **orbital AI compute satellites as early as 2028**.\n    *   The Anthropic contract and the $805 million terrestrial turbine purchases run through 2029.\n*   **Long-Term (End of Decade & 2030):** \n    *   The company\'s goal is to launch **100 gigawatts of compute to space each year** by the end of the decade. \n    *   The filing notes the macroeconomic context that the global market requires $7 trillion in data center investments through 2030 to meet AI demands, positioning the company\'s orbital and terrestrial roadmap to capture this growth.',
