stments in **launch site infrastructure for Starship**.\n* **Connectivity:** Increases were driven by higher **satellite and ground equipment costs** to expand the Starlink satellite network and drive subscriber growth.\n* **AI:** Explosive growth in CapEx was driven by the **rapid expansion of terrestrial data centers**, including the development, construction, and equipping of new facilities and supporting infrastructure.\n\n### 3. Future Investment Commitments by Key Initiative\n\n#### **Starship (Space Segment)**\n* **Investment Scale:** Starship requires the investment of "significant additional capital resources." In 2025, the Space segment funded **$3.0 billion in R&D expenses** specifically for the Starship program (up from $1.8 billion in 2024).\n* **Future Accounting Shift:** The company expects Space R&D expenses to increase in 2026 as it invests in Starship\'s development and commercialization. However, **once Starship is commercialized** (delivering payload to orbit), costs will generally shift from expensed R&D to **capitalized assets**, which will then be depreciated in the cost of revenue.\n* **Strategic Goal:** Starship is central to the company\'s vertically integrated model. By achieving full reusability and massive payload capacity (100 to 200 metric tons), it is expected to **reduce the cost to reach orbit by 99% or more**, establishing the foundational infrastructure for future "orbital AI compute."\n\n#### **Terafab (Manufacturing & Compute)**\n* **Definition & Goal:** The filing defines "Terafab" as a **chip manufacturing initiative** with the long-term goal of producing **one terawatt of compute**. \n* **CapEx Inclusion:** Terafab is explicitly listed alongside AI compute infrastructure and data centers as a primary driver for the company\'s anticipated substantial increases in future capital expenditures.\n\n#### **AI Data Centers & Compute Infrastructure (AI Segment)**\n* **Multi-Year Investment Horizon:** The company expects a "multi-year