ely on Starship\'s economics. Starship is expected to reduce the cost to reach orbit by 99% or more. The filing explicitly warns: *"AI compute satellites at scale need full Starship reusability to be economically compelling."* Without rapid turnaround and full reusability, the orbital AI program would suffer from a slower pace and prohibitively higher costs.\n*   **Deployment Mechanics (The "PEZ Dispenser"):** To handle the massive volume of satellites without requiring complex, risky in-orbit assembly, the company plans to leverage Starship\'s **"PEZ dispenser system."** This integrated payload deployment system allows for the rapid, automated dispensing of fully deployable single-unit satellites directly into orbit.\n*   **Proven Survivability:** The AI compute satellites will leverage the V3 satellite platform. The filing notes that existing Starlink satellites have already proven they can survive the intense launch environment of Starship (vibration, shock, g-loads, acoustic stress, and vacuum exposure), achieving 99.9% average uptime.\n*   **A Critical Single Point of Failure (Risk Dependency):** The orbital AI timeline is highly vulnerable to Starship\'s development. The Risk Factors section warns that any delays in Starship\'s flight testing, manufacturing scale-up, infrastructure build-out (like propellant plants), or FAA regulatory approvals would *"materially and adversely affect"* the company\'s ability to deploy orbital AI compute infrastructure. \n\nIn summary, the filing positions **Starship as the absolute prerequisite** for orbital AI. Without Starship\'s massive payload capacity, "PEZ dispenser" deployment mechanics, and fully reusable cost structure, the company\'s vision of moving power-intensive AI workloads into orbit to harness unlimited solar energy would not be commercially or physically viable.',
